###############################################################################################
# Description: This .dat file allows you to configure what type of build you want to perform for a selection of
# the software that is used. 
# The word "source" means build from source and the word "repo" means build from standard repositories
# The advantage to building from source is that you can easily fork the repositories and modify the configuration
# parameters in the script if your configuration requirements are different to what I have set by default.
# The disadvantage to building from source is that the machines take longer to build and configure. 
# Author Peter Winter
# Date 07/06/2016
##############################################################################################
# The set of possible configurations you could have are as follows:
# If you are building for NGINX (your template webserver is set to NGINX) you can select one of:
# NGINX:source   
# NGINX:git-branch:<git-branch> (takes precedence over NGINX:sourcecode_url if set)
# NGINX:sourcecode_url:<url>
# NGINX:modules-list:<module1>:<module2>:....<modulen> (only applies when building nginx using apt)
# NGINX:static-modules-list:<module1>:<module2>:....<modulen> (only applies when building nginx from source)
# NGINX:software-packages:<software-package1>:<software-package2>:.....<modulen>
# NGINX:repo:os (only one of repo:os or repo:official when performing a repo based build)
# NGINX:repo:official
# NGINX:mainline (uncomment this if you are installing from official repositories and you want to install the mainline version rather than the stable version)
# If you are building for APACHE (your templates webserver is set to APACHE) you can select one of:
# APACHE:source  
# APACHE:sourcecode_url:<url>
# APACHE:sha256_url:<url>
# APACHE:sha512_url:<url>
# APACHE:apr_sourcecode_url:<url>
# APACHE:apr_sha256_url:<url>
# APACHE:apr_util_sourcecode_url:<url>
# APACHE:apr_util_sha256_url:<url>
# APACHE:modules-list:<module1>:<module2>:....<modulen>
# APACHE:static-modules-list:<module1>:<module2>:....<modulen> (only applies when building apache from source)
# APACHE:software-packages:<software-package1>:<software-package2>:.....<modulen>
# APACHE:repo
# If you are building for lighttpd (your template webserver is set to LIGHTTPD) you can select one of:
# LIGHTTPD:source   
# LIGHTTPD:sourcecode_url:<url>
# LIGHTTPD:sha256_url:<url>
# LIGHTTPD:sha512_url:<url>
# LIGHTTPD:modules-list:<module1>:<module2>:....<modulen>
# LIGHTTPD:static-modules-list:<module1>:<module2>:....<modulen> (only applies when building lighttpd from source)
# LIGHTTPD:software-packages:<software-package1>:<software-package2>:.....<modulen>
# LIGHTTPD:repo
# You can define what extensions PHP will be built with by modifying the line starting PHP: as shown below
# PHP:<extension1>:<extension2>|port
# If you have PERSIST_ASSETS_TO_DATASTORE=1 then you need a datastore mount tool, you can install from repo or from source and your options are:
# DATASTOREMOUNTTOOL:s3fs:repo
# DATASTOREMOUNTTOOL:s3fs:source
# DATASTOREMOUNTTOOL:goof:binary
# DATASTOREMOUNTTOOL:goof:source
# DATASTOREMOUNTTOOL:rclone:repo
# DATASTOREMOUNTTOOL:rclone:binary
# DATASTOREMOUNTTOOL:rclone:script
# DATASTOREMOUNTTOOL:rclone:source #if you choose this option you will need at least 50GB of disk space for your servers to be able to install properly (a nanode wan't enough, for example, in my testing)
# DATASTOREMOUNTTOOL:geesefs:binary
# DATASTOREMOUNTTOOL:geesefs:source
# There are three different methods for maintaining the state of your configuration system and you can set which one to use as follows:
# DATASTORECONFIGSTYLE:tool
# DATASTORECONFIGSTYLE:lightweight
# DATASTORECONFIGSTYLE:heavyweight
# If you want to unify different individual mount points as one file system you will need a filesystem merge tool
# MERGEFILESYSTEMSTOOL:mergefs:repo
# MERGEFILESYSTEMSTOOL:mergefs:binary
# When installing mariadb on your VPS systems you can give it a verion number to install like this 
# If you put 'cloud-init' here then cloud-init will install the default version of mariadb
# MARIADB:cloud-init
# MARIADB:repo:<version>
# MySQL can be installed similarly to mariadb but there is no cloud-init option. You just tell it the version number you want to install and that its not cloud-init
# You need to get your MySQL version number from https://dev.mysql.com/downloads/mysql (for example, 9.2.0)
# MYSQL:repo:<version>
# When installing postgres on your VPS systems you can give a version number to install like this
# POSTGRES:repo:<version>
# The buildchain type will define what usecase you are deploying. Standard will deploy autoscaler,webserver and database. database will deploy database only and webserver will deploy webserver only
# Developers could define other chain node types such as caching for example and then caching would deploy a caching node such as memcached or redis and so on
# BUILDCHAINTYPE:standard|webserver|database
# The tool used for datastore access is an abstraction and you can use other tools rclone, s4cmd and to implement the interface if you want
# DATASTORETOOL:s3cmd:repo
# DATASTORETOOL:s3cmd:source
# DATASTORETOOL:s5cmd:binary
# DATASTORETOOL:s5cmd:source
# CLOUDCLITOOL:repo|binary
# You can set how you want to install your cloud cli tool from the different available installation methods
# CLOUDCLITOOL:doctl:snap
# CLOUDCLITOOL:doctl:binary
# CLOUDCLITOOL:linode-cli:pip
# CLOUDCLITOOL:linode-cli:snap
# CLOUDCLITOOL:exo:repo
# CLOUDCLITOOL:exo:source
# CLOUDCLITOOL:vultr:binary
# CLOUDCLITOOL:vultr:source
# You can install the GO language from binary or repo
# GO:repo
# GO:binary
# You can choose which package manager you want to use. Currently only apt and apt-get are supported mostly as an example of how multiple package managers can be implemented. 
# PACKAGEMANAGER:apt|apt-get
# You can choose what style of firewall you would like to have by setting the FIREWALL. You can choose ufw or iptables
# FIREWALL:ufw|iptables
# By default there is no rate limiting if you want to set rate limiting for ports open to the Internet such as 443 (possibly) then
# you can rate limit as follows
# FIREWALL:ufw:limit (when limit is set ufw will deny connections if an IP address attempts to initiate six or more connections within thirty seconds)
# FIREALL:iptables:20:30 (20 represents the limit on the number of connections per minute from a single ip address and 30 represenets the burst rate limit)
# if you want to use fail2ban you can set this will install fail2ban on all your machines
# FAIL2BAN:active|inactive
# You can choose which email utility you want to send your system emails using sendemail or ssmtp
# EMAILUTIL:sendemail|ssmtp
# You can choose which tool you want to use to generate your ssl certificates
# SSLCERTCLIENT:lego|acme (note: if you are using letsencrypt you must set this to 'lego' if you are using zerossl you must set this to 'acme')
# For letsencrypt you have to install lego
# SSLCERTCLIENT:lego:binary
# SSLCERTCLIENT:lego:snap
# For zerossl you have to install acme.sh - You can install from acme.sh or github.com
# SSLCERTCLIENT:acme:acme.sh
# SSLCERTCLIENT:acme:github.com
# GITBRANCH:main|dev
# You can create branches as you need to but currently there is a main branch and a dev branch to work with
# You can scan for viruses on your servers on a periodic basis VIRUSSCANNER:clamav:hourly|daily|weekly|monthly
# VIRUSSCANNER:clamav:daily
